                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="http://twitter.com/intent/tweet?url=https://www.dukechronicle.com/article/2004/07/ncaa-frustrations-may-drive-krzyzewski-nba&amp;text=NCAA frustrations may drive Krzyzewski to NBA" target="_blank" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="twitter" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fab fa-twitter"></i></a></li>
                                                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="mailto:?subject=NCAA%20frustrations%20may%20drive%20Krzyzewski%20to%20NBA%20|%20The%20Chronicle&amp;message=Check%20out%20this%20article%20from%20The%20Chronicle%3A%20https%3A%2F%2Fwww.dukechronicle.com%2Farticle%2F2004%2F07%2Fncaa-frustrations-may-drive-krzyzewski-nba" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="email" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fa fa-envelope"></i></a></li>
                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="#" onclick="window.print()" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="facebook" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fas fa-print"></i></a></li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                
                <div class="article-content w-100 mb-4">
                                            <p>Tinsel Town or Tobacco Road?</p>
<p>This is the question men&rsquo;s basketball head coach Mike Krzyzewski will be contemplating this weekend, as he attempts to decide whether to remain in Durham or to venture to the NBA&rsquo;s Los Angeles Lakers. In his 24 seasons at Duke, Krzyzewski has served as one of college basketball&rsquo;s most vociferous advocates, although he has grown increasingly frustrated with the NCAA and the trend that continues to send the nation&rsquo;s best young talent to the professional ranks prematurely.</p>

                        <div class="inline-ad float-none float-md-left my-4 mr-0 mr-md-4 text-center d-print-none">
                            <!-- START gryphon/ads/rectangle-inline.tpl -->
            <div id="azk18664"></div>
    <!-- END gryphon/ads/rectangle-inline.tpl -->
                        </div>

                        <p>&ldquo;What he loves the most&mdash;it&rsquo;s not beating people&mdash;it&rsquo;s taking an 18-year old kid and producing a 22-year old man,&rdquo; Senior Associate Athletic Director Chris Kennedy said. &ldquo;The Shane Battier, the Johnny Dawkins&mdash;to have these polished, accomplished, admirable individuals come out of our program&mdash;that&rsquo;s what he&rsquo;s seen as his central mission. Now it&rsquo;s sort of leaking away.&rdquo;</p>
<p>This drain could be one of the primary reasons Krzyzewski is so strongly considering a deal that would send him to the Los Angeles Lakers. The money, sources claim, is a secondary factor&mdash;despite the $40 million dollar contract the Lakers have reportedly offered.</p>
<p>&ldquo;What bothers [Krzyzewski] more than anything else is the way things have gotten so out of kilter,&rdquo; Kennedy said.</p>
<p>Prior to the 1998-99 season, Krzyzewski&rsquo;s Duke teams had never lost a player leaving to NBA before his senior year of college. Since then, however, a total of eight have sacrificed their amateur status for the pros, including Shaun Livingston, who was Duke&rsquo;s first player to commit but never even set foot on campus as a student.</p>
<p>&ldquo;For the last five, six, seven years, there&rsquo;s been a real shift in college basketball [away] from four years. For years you were operating from a stable platform, and your basic recruiting platform was to replace your current juniors,&rdquo; Kennedy said. &ldquo;You had a platform. And that&rsquo;s all exploded.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Indeed, Krzyzewski, 57, has built a program as powerful and consistent as the NCAA has seen in the past several decades, as his squads have won three national championships and been ranked No. 1 in each of the past seven seasons.</p>

                        <div class="inline-ad float-none float-md-left my-4 mr-0 mr-md-4 text-center d-print-none">
                            <!-- START gryphon/ads/rectangle-article-5.tpl -->
        <div id="azk5125"></div>
<!-- END gryphon/ads/rectangle-article-5.tpl -->
                        </div>

                                                                            <p>When Krzyzewski took control of Duke&rsquo;s program, however, winning was much harder to come by.</p>
<p>&ldquo;It was a great time to be there, to be there during the building process,&rdquo; said Tom Mickle, who worked in the Duke athletic department throughout the 1980s. &ldquo;He came in and didn&rsquo;t have a whole lot of talent left from the previous team. There were a lot of critics at that point in time. Mainly Coach K took the brunt of it.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Mickle recalled sitting in a Denny&rsquo;s restaurant the night of one the worst losses in Krzyzewski&rsquo;s career, a 109-66 loss to Virginia in the first round of the ACC Tournament at the conclusion of the 1982-83 campaign, Krzyzewski&rsquo;s third. It was the painful culmination of Duke&rsquo;s second consecutive losing season.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Coach K always had a vision for where he wanted the program to go and he was very focused and he stayed with it,&rdquo; Mickle said. &ldquo;I remember everybody being in a panic except for Coach K. And he said, &lsquo;No, we&rsquo;re staying with the plan.&rsquo; He had this faith and it carried him through.... There&rsquo;s nothing greater than coming from the bottom to the top.&rdquo;</p>
                            

<div class="mc-signup my-4 p-4 text-center " id="mc-container" data-mc="58dfdea1a4">
    <h3>Get Overtime, all Duke athletics</h3>
    <p>Signup for our editorially curated, weekly newsletter. Cancel at any time.</p>
    <div class="row">
        <div class="col col-md-8 offset-md-2">
            <form action="//dukechronicle.us4.list-manage.com/subscribe/post?u=c49dc69f492af7f2727860d0b&amp;id=58dfdea1a4" method="post">
