                    <div class="input-group-append">
                        <input type="submit" value="Subscribe" class="btn btn-secondary btn-sm sends-events" data-ga-category="CTA" data-ga-action="email_focus" data-ga-label="58dfdea1a4" />
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div style="position: absolute; left: -5000px;"><input type="text" name="b_c49dc69f492af7f2727860d0b_58dfdea1a4" tabindex="-1" value=""></div>

            </form>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>
                        
                        <p>Essential to the Blue Devils&rsquo; rise was Krzyzewski&rsquo;s emphasis on the importance of team-play, as demonstrated by his famed &ldquo;fist&rdquo; metaphor, in which five players come together as one on the court. But would Krzyzewski be able to produce the same results from coaching in the NBA, where player and team development are often an afterthought?</p>
<p>&ldquo;I don&rsquo;t know the answer to that,&rdquo; Kennedy said. &ldquo;Maybe he decides, &lsquo;The other challenge isn&rsquo;t there anymore, I&rsquo;m going to opt for an alternate challenge.&rsquo;&rdquo;</p>
<p>Kennedy said he believes the challenges Krzyzewski faces as a college coach have changed significantly since 1990, when the Boston Celtics were clamoring for his services. At the time, he was yet to bring home a national title.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I think that at the time he thought he had a lot left to do in college basketball,&rdquo; Kennedy said. &ldquo;I think now, he&rsquo;s done things that he&rsquo;d love to accomplish [again], but they&rsquo;d be repetitious in a way.&rdquo;</p>
<p>NCAA politics and the league&rsquo;s plethora of rules and restrictions may also be weighing on Krzyzewski&rsquo;s mind.</p>
<p>&ldquo;As I look at being a Division I basketball coach these days, I think those are things that after a while would begin to get old,&rdquo; Kennedy said.</p>
<p>Regardless, Athletic Director Joe Alleva made it clear at a press conference Thursday that the University will do whatever it takes to keep Krzyzewski at Duke. In terms of his salary, however, Duke simply cannot compete with the resources of the Lakers.</p>
<p>&ldquo;We cannot match financially what the Lakers are going to offer&mdash;we just can&rsquo;t do it,&rdquo; Kennedy said. &ldquo;And it wouldn&rsquo;t be appropriate for us to do it. We&rsquo;re talking about University resources that need to be distributed across a wide range of programs for some very important things. But Mike understands that, too.&rdquo;</p>

                                                    <div class="related my-4 py-4 d-print-none">
                                <h3 class="kicker mb-4">Read more</h3>

                                                                                                                
            
        
    <article class="art-hed mb-4">
        <h3><a href="https://www.dukechronicle.com/article/2019/12/duke-womens-basketball-acc-preview-2019-2020">Taking a look at Duke women&#039;s basketball&#039;s ACC competition</a></h3>
                            <hr />
            </article>

                                                                                
            
        
    <article class="art-hed mb-4">
        <h3><a href="https://www.dukechronicle.com/article/2019/12/thoughts-on-the-ap-poll-duke-mens-basketball-rises">Thoughts on the AP poll: Duke men&#039;s basketball rises to No. 7</a></h3>
                            <hr />
            </article>

                                                                                
            
        
    <article class="art-hed">
        <h3><a href="https://www.dukechronicle.com/article/2019/12/duke-basketball-podcasts-joey-baker-tre-jones-vernon-carey">Cameron Chronicles Season 3, Episode 3: &#039;Road Warriors&#039;</a></h3>
                    </article>

                                                                                                </div>
                        

                        <p>And though Krzyzewski has been awarded what amounts to a lifetime contract, an appointment as special assistant to the President and a faculty position in the Fuqua School of Business, Kennedy said there is plenty Duke can still offer its most famous coach. The package could include a brand-new practice facility that would complement the Schwartz-Butters building, completed in 1999, that houses locker rooms, basketball offices and Duke basketball&rsquo;s Hall of Fame.</p>
<p>&ldquo;There are some things that the University can do that he would like,&rdquo; Kennedy noted. &ldquo;This practice facility has actually been in the works for a while. But there may be other things. It comes down to him deciding, &lsquo;Is this a different direction I want to take in my life?&rsquo; regardless of who offers what. He&rsquo;s never been a guy that&rsquo;s been motivated by money.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Currently, the Blue Devils hold their practices in Cameron Indoor Stadium and in the adjacent Card Gymnasium. Kennedy was quick to point out, however, that Krzyzewksi is not the only one interested in supplementing Duke&rsquo;s athletic facilities with another basketball court.</p>
<p>&ldquo;To have a facility that gets the basketball team out of Card Gym altogether, and opens Cameron to volleyball and wrestling and all of those things, would be helpful to us all,&rdquo; Kennedy said. &ldquo;The architect has done drawings, and they&rsquo;ve looked at locations all around campus. This has been going on for a while.&rdquo;</p>
<p>But despite Duke&rsquo;s willingness to persuade Krzyzewski to remain in Durham, Kennedy would not be surprised if the Hall of Famer headed to Los Angeles.</p>
<p>&ldquo;My heart tells me that he&rsquo;ll stay, but evaluating everything that&rsquo;s been going on, and everything the Lakers can offer him, and his own kind of thirst&mdash;he&rsquo;s a very, very competitive guy,&rdquo; Kennedy speculated. &ldquo;And I think that maybe in the back of his mind for a long time he&rsquo;s thought, &lsquo;I could compete with Phil Jackson or Red Auerbach or whoever you think of as a great NBA coach&rsquo;... But from time to time, he&rsquo;s had to have wondered how he would do on that stage.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Krzyzewski&rsquo;s passion for competition is perhaps only rivaled by his love for his family and his reputably magnetic personality. Former Athletic Director Tom Butters, who hired the then-unknown coach from West Point in 1980, lauded Krzyzewski for much more than his ability to win on the court.</p>
<p>&ldquo;He is a remarkable man and he is an outstanding talent as a coach,&rdquo; Butters said. &ldquo;And one of the things is that he&rsquo;ll be as good a coach as he is a person.&rdquo;</p>
<p>It is not surprising, then, that Krzyzewski&rsquo;s ultimate decision may hinge on the feelings of his wife, Mickie.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I know that Mickie and Mike are a team,&rdquo; Kennedy said. &ldquo;And Mike places a lot of stock, and rightly so, on what Mickie thinks.... If Mike comes to her and says, &lsquo;We have a great life here and a great home and people love us and we&rsquo;re secure, but this is something we have to do,&rsquo; then Mickie&rsquo;s going to say, &lsquo;Follow me, I&rsquo;m going to lead us out there.&rsquo;&rdquo;</p>
<p><i>Kelly Rohrs contributed to this story.</i></p>
                                    </div>

